# Keymaker Project Rules

## Product philosophy (non-negotiable)

- No upvotes, downvotes, agree/disagree, or single karma number.
- Evaluation is four-axis only: clarity, evidence, kindness, novelty.
- Do not silently introduce traditional social-media mechanics (likes, hearts, popularity scores).
- Schema and UI must support multidimensional evaluation; do not flatten to one score in the product.

## Code and architecture

- Keep code maintainable and explicit. Prefer TypeScript and strong typing.
- Keep business logic out of controllers; put it in services.
- Ranking, aggregate recomputation, and reputation updates live in services only.
- Never trust client-supplied aggregate or ranking values; always compute server-side.
- Validate all write inputs.
- Keep the ranking formula readable and easy to modify.
- Avoid premature optimization and clever abstractions unless they clearly reduce complexity.
- Use clear naming over short naming.
- Document major tradeoffs in comments or README.

## Operations and data

- Prefer simple deployment over extra infrastructure.
- Keep PostgreSQL schema clean and migration-safe.
- Favor soft deletes for posts/comments where practical.

## Dependencies and scope

- Avoid adding dependencies unless clearly justified.
- Build the MVP first; do not drift into nonessential features.
- Keep the project easy for one developer to own and extend.

## UI

- UI should be minimal, readable, and functional.
